\n[[Category:2002 establishments in New York City]]\n", "name_user": "Int21h", "label": "safe", "comment": "the Education Law is a named chapter of the Consolidated Laws of New York", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City_Department_of_Education"}
{"title_page": "Zimbabwean art", "text_new": "{{See also|Sculpture of Zimbabwe}}\n'''Zimbabwean [[art]]''' includes decorative [[esthetics]] applied to many aspects of life, including [[art object]]s as such, utilitarian objects, objects used in religion, warfare, in [[propaganda]], and in many other spheres. Within this broad arena, [[Zimbabwe]] has several identifiable categories of art. It is a hallmark of [[African culture]]s in general that art touches many aspects of life, and most tribes have a vigorous and often recognisable canon of styles and a great range of art-worked objects. These can include [[mask]]s, [[drum]]s, [[textile]] decoration, beadwork, carving, [[Sculpture of Zimbabwe|sculpture]], [[ceramic]] in various forms, housing and the person themselves. Decoration of the body in permanent ways such as [[scarification]] or [[tattoo]] or impermanently as in painting the body for a ceremony is a common feature of African cultures.\n\nSpoken or musical art is also a prominent part of Africas generally. Various instruments including drums, lamellophones and stringed bows have been used in Zimbabwe, while oratory, poetry, fable telling, praise singing and tribal ritual chants are also prominent.\n\nIn recent decades Zimbabwe has become widely recognized internationally for its [[Sculpture of Zimbabwe|sculpture]].\n\n==History==\nIt is useful to examine Zimbabwean art through time, by area, by main tribal division and as indicative of recent historic and political changes.\n\nThere is an artistic tradition in [[Zimbabwe]] that can be traced back to [[pottery]] of the [[Early Stone Age|Early]] and [[Late Stone Age]] and [[rock paintings]] from the Late Stone Age.<ref>Winter-Irving C. (1991) \"Visual Culture in Early History\", Chapter 8 in \"Stone Sculpture in Zimbabwe\", Roblaw Publishers, [[Harare]], {{ISBN|0908309147}}</ref> Many rock paintings produced by [[Bushmen|San]] artists between 10000 and 2000 years ago are found in cultural sites in Zimbabwe <ref>Garlake P S. (1993) \"Painted Caves: Prehistoric Art in Zimbabwe\", Modus Publications Pvt. Ltd, {{ISBN|0908309007}}</ref> and these demonstrate a high degree of skill in drawing. Many depict recognisable animal figures and use shading and colour to enhance the visual impact. The [[archaeology]] of Zimbabwe includes numerous pottery finds, which assist in the reconstruction of linguistic and cultural groupings within what is here termed [[Shona people|Shona]].<ref>Beach D N. (1980) \"Shona and Zimbabwe 900-1850: An Outline of Shona History\", Heinemann, {{ISBN|043594505X}}</ref> The pottery indicates that the people of the [[Late Iron Age]] were settled [[agriculturists]] and they have been categorised as forming groups such as the Harare culture and the Leopard\u2019s Kopje culture: the latter established in 980 AD in a site called K2.<ref>Huffman T. (1986) \"Iron Age Settlements and Origins of Class Distinction in Southern Africa\", Advances in World Archaeology, vol. 5, pp.291-338</ref> This group moved to [[Mapungubwe]] where they used stone walls to separate the ruling class from the rest of the population. This settlement was abandoned in the thirteenth century at around the time that a now much better-known site was developed by others who lived on the Zimbabwean plateau. This was [[Great Zimbabwe]], which dates from about 1250\u20131500 AD. It is a stone-walled town (''Zimbabwe'' means \"royal residence\") and shows evidence in its archaeology of skilled stone working: the walls were made of a local granite and no mortar was used in their construction.<ref>Needham D.E., Mashingaidze E.K, Bhebe N. (1984) \"From Iron Age to Independence, A History of Central Africa\", p17. Longman, England. {{ISBN|0582651115}}</ref> When excavated, [[Zimbabwe bird|six soapstone birds]] and a [[soapstone]] bowl were found in the eastern enclosure of the monument, so these [[Shona language|Shona-speaking]] Gumanye people certainly produced sculpture. Each object was carved from a single piece of stone and the birds have an aesthetic quality that places them as genuine \"art\". In comparing them to other better-known African stone sculpture, for example from the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba culture]], Philip Allison, writing in 1968, stated \"The stone sculptures of Rhodesia are few in number and of no great aesthetic distinction, but Zimbabwe itself has a place of peculiar importance in the study of African cultures\".<ref>Allison P., (1968) \"African Stone Sculpture\", p54. Lund Humphries, Great Britain</ref>\n\n===Stone Age===\nIn prehistory the area was widely settled by Kung peoples, the so-called [[Khoikhoi]] or San, Hottentot or Bushmen people, who were [[hunter gatherer]]s. They often lived in [[caves]] and made various artworks, including beading from shells for personal decoration, incising designs on [[ostrich]] shells and utilitarian objects such as clay water straws and also on the cave walls themselves. These dynamic and varied [[cave paintings]] date from around 10000 BCE and depict humans hunting many kinds of animals, warfare between humans, mystical and other unidentified marks, landscape and ceremonies where the humans are obviously decorated or in costume. The colours vary from black through brown, red, [[ochre]], yellow and white. The pigments used are unknown, though presumably contain a mix of local materials such as earth [[oxides]], fat, vegetable juices and possibly fluids from [[larva]]l insects. Certainly they have lasted for thousands of years.\n\nTheir descendants, who live mainly in Botswana and Namibia, sing a variety of uniquely structured and tuneful songs, accompanied sometimes by a plucked or struck bow. They also have a repertoire of dances, and there is no reason to suspect their ancestors did not do the same thing.\n\n===Iron Age===\nThese Stone Age people were supplanted by Iron Age [[Nguni people|Nguni]]-derived pastoral and farming peoples migrating in from the east and north around 2000 years ago, who became the ancestors of the [[Rozwi Empire|WaRozwi]]/Barotse people and by derivation the [[Amashona]] peoples. The art of these people can be seen in many decorated first-fired clay pots, where typically a repeated dhlo-dhlo (linear [[herringbone pattern|herringbone]]) [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] or similar edging was applied. Other artwork is harder to source, though it can assumed they decorated the body and had [[beadwork]] and other art styles related to typical styles of the East and Central African Nguni peoples. A recurrent motif in Shona art is the transformation of a human into an animal of some kind.\n\n===Later prehistory===\nAt around the same time as the earlier incursions of these Bantu-type people (200BCE) there were sporadic expeditions by South-East coastal dwellers, probably by the [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]] or over mountain passes in the [[Eastern Highlands]], into the Zimbabwe area to obtain [[gold]] for trade with [[Arab]] traders trading as far south as the mouth of the Savi. They built stone forts extending into the interior at one day's march from each other, with the final one being the complex now known as [[Great Zimbabwe]]. To service the coastal trade a town called [[Sofala]] was established at the  mouth of the Sofala river on the east coast. It had its heydey in around 700 AD/CE and served the [[Mwenemutapa]]/[[Monomotapa]] Kingdom, whose capital was [[Great Zimbabwe]]. Arabs took up residence in Sofala around 900AD/CE.\n\n===Early sculpture===\nArchaeology at Zimbabwe has shown several distinct phases of building and styles of stonework. It is likely the original complex was rather functional - essentially a [[fort]] and trading post only, and the later and more elaborate building occurred when the complex became the central administrative and royal centre of activity for the area. Some of the architectural features are probably linked with styles of coastal [[Swahili architecture]] and some are uniquely local. [[Chinese pottery]] shards, ivory, glass objects, local gold objects, Arabic and local beads, [[copper ingot]]s, [[iron]] ingots and other trade items have been found at Zimbabwe. The herringbone and other stepped linear forms of decoration in the walls are a feature of the most recent stonework. Similar stonework is seen at [[Khami]] ruins, a fort built on the way to Zimbabwe. However, the most impressive and unique feature of Zimbabwe are the huge [[soapstone birds]], the so-called [[Zimbabwe bird]]s, depicting a [[bird of prey]] perched on a zig-zag base motif. These birds are possibly based on the [[bateleur eagle]] or maybe a [[vulture]] species and might have had something to do with a [[Cult|religious cult]] or indicative of a [[totem]] animal for the ruling people at the time. Most of these sculptures are still in the country but one is in South Africa where it still adorns [[Groote Schuur]] an official residence, once the home of Cecil Rhodes. Another unexplained motif at Zimbabwe, which like the birds were mounted on the perimeter wall of the Great Enclosure, were stelae or tall narrow rectilinear pillars of rock (probably natural fracture artefacts) set at intervals round the top of the wall. The Zimbabwe bird is the most prominent motif of the current [[Zimbabwe flag]].\n\n===Amandebele incursions===\nThe origin of [[Amandebele]] speaking peoples in southern Zimbabwe received its main impetus from settlement around 1840 under Mzilikazi, a Khumalo chief who rebelled against Zulu rule. However, it is likely that such tribes began crossing the Limpopo sporadically from about 1800 onwards. Amandebele conflict with the Amashona drove them northwards into what was dubbed in colonial times Mashonaland. These [[Amandebele]]/[[Northern Ndebele people|Matabele]] peoples had several distinct art forms differing from the Amashona: in pottery styles, bead aprons and headpieces, house decoration, carving and decoration of war implements such as clubs/[[knobkierrie]]s and shields.\n\n===19th and early 20th century===\nArt in Zimbabwe lost most of its spiritual power with the conversion of the majority of the population to Christianity in the 19th and 20th centuries. Missionaries harmed the local cultures by demanding destruction of anything they regarded as anti-Christian, in particular masks or carvings thought to have votive powers, that is, to be appealing to some god that was not the Christian one. By the second world war most art objects produced in Zimbabwe were simply that: produced for tourist and local white settler consumption. With the advent of guns, animal skins prepared and decorated with small panels of other hides also began to appear more frequently in the early 20th century, as well as '[[kaross]]es' or fur blankets influenced by BaTchwana styles from Botswana to the south.\n\nAs for travelers to the area during the [[Victorian period]], they used art, especially painting, to depict some of what they saw there. This art of the [[colony|colonial period]] took landscape as its main theme and many of the European artists were present as part of expeditions that aimed to inform the public in Europe about life in Africa. For example, [[Thomas Baines]] joined the [[Zambezi]] expedition led by [[David Livingstone]] in 1858 and in 1861 he was one of the first to make oil paintings of [[Victoria Falls, Zambia|Victoria Falls]]. [[John Guille Millais]] spent six months of 1893 sketching and hunting in Zimbabwe.<ref name=CWI9>Winter-Irving C. (1991) \"Visual Arts since the Nineteenth Century\", Chapter 9 in \"Stone Sculpture in Zimbabwe\", Roblaw Publishers, [[Harare]], {{ISBN|0908309147}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1940s a Zimbabwe philanthropist named [[Jairos Jiri]] began to teach disabled people various artistic skills and centralised their production for sale in several outlets nationwide. These proved very popular and returned money to persons otherwise excluded from normal commercial activity. Jairos Jiri centres remain an important part of the artistic output in Zimbabwe. Typical items include tiles, tiled tables and wall plaques, basketwork, beading, carvings in wood and stone, jewellery and paintings.\n\n===Prelude to independence===\nIn the mid-1970s the nationalist guerilla incursions resulted in several atrocities against people in rural villages, including the sawing off of the upper lip of those perceived as collaborating with the government forces. The white government collated photographic images and a text list of these events into a propaganda booklet called 'Anatomy of Terror'. This was designed to show the brutality of the nationalists against innocent rural native people. Images from this publication are today to be found on [[YouTube]] (for example under 'Terrorists in the Rhodesian bush').\n\nOther art from the white minority during the civil \"Rhodesian Bush\" (1968 - 1979) war consisted mainly of depictions of indigenous fauna and flora and landscapes. These subjects had always been popular and remain popular to this day among white artists. No individual white artist expressed any significant political sentiment during the civil war era. However, many film, still and sound clips celebrating the government forces' role during this time are currently available on YouTube.\n\n===Painting in the 20th century===\nWhile there were many well-known white artists in Rhodesia prior to independence in 1980, there were relatively few black artists of note. One of these was [[Kingsley Sambo]] (1932\u20131977), who started to paint at the [[Cyrene Mission]] where Canon Edward Paterson taught art. Two of Sambo\u2019s paintings are in the [[Museum of Modern Art in New York|MoMA]]. Others were [[Thomas Mukarobgwa]] (also a leading sculptor) and [[Joseph Ndandarika]] <ref>Zilberg J. (2006) [http://www.nationalgallery.co.zw/PDFs/Kinglsey%20Sambo%20and%20Vincent%20Van%20Gogh.pdf]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} National Gallery archive</ref>\n\nAlthough the Workshop School of the National Gallery supported and encouraged painters from 1957, Rhodesia had few Colleges for Fine Arts. The Bulawayo College of Fine Art and Design trained artists in fine art and graphic design for Rhodesian industry and it was not until 1963 that Alex Lambert set up the [[Mzilikazi Art School]] in [[Bulawayo]] specifically to encourage local people to take up art.\n\nThe [[National Gallery of Zimbabwe|National Gallery]] has, since 1986, promoted local artists by hosting an annual exhibition of contemporary visual arts called \"Zimbabwe Heritage\". Patronage from Zimbabwean companies \u2013 the Baringa Corporation (for paintings, graphics, textiles, ceramics and photograph) and the Nedlaw Investment and Trust Corporation (for sculpture) \u2013 initially supported the expense of having an international panel of judges come to Zimbabwe to assess the works and make Awards. Later, the sponsorship of the event grew to include international companies such as [[Mobil]], [[Lever Brothers]], [[The BOC Group]] and [[Longman]]. Early winners of Awards of Distinction in the painters and graphics category included Berry Bickle (1987), Bert Hemsteede (1988), Rashid Jogee (1992) and Tichaona Madzamba (1992).<ref name=NGZ>See annual catalogues for ''Zimbabwe Heritage'', produced by the [[National Gallery of Zimbabwe|National Gallery]]</ref>\n\nPainters who have established reputations in post-independence Zimbabwe include [[Dumisani Ngwenya]], [[Taylor Nkomo]] and [[Richard Jack]].<ref name=CWI9/>\n\n===Sculpture in the 20th and 21st centuries===\n[[File:Zimbabwe sculpture at Atlanta airport.JPG|thumb|''[[Zimbabwe Sculpture: a Tradition in Stone]]'', [[Atlanta]], United States, at [[Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport]] between concourses T and A]]\n\n{{Main|Sculpture of Zimbabwe}}\n[[Chapungu Sculpture Park]] in [[Harare]] is currently an important locality for display of (mainly) Shona sculptors and carvers. Another [http://www.chapungusculpturepark.com Chapungu Sculpture Park] was created in 2007 in the United States, along with a gallery, in Loveland, Colorado. ''[[Zimbabwe Sculpture: a Tradition in Stone]]'' is on permanent display at [[Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta's airport]].\n\n[[AVAC Arts]] URL [[www.avacarts.com]] is another vital pace-setting player in the Zimbabwe contemporary arts sector promoting adaptation and utilization of new technologies and runs an online portal facilitating international art trade and promotion of Zimbabwean stone sculptures.\n\nSince antiquity local artists have been using the steatite/[[soapstone]] deposits of the eastern Zimbabwe mountain ranges to produce artworks showing, among other things, the common Shona theme of animal/human inter-morphosis. These works became much larger under the patronage of white collectors in the 1960s (though the Zimbabwe birds of antiquity are massive) and now it is common to see monumental soapstone sculptures both nationally and internationally.\n\nNoted Zimbabwean artists include sculptor [[Patrick Mavros]], and painters [[Kim Donaldson]], [[Larry Norton]], [[Brennan Seward]], [[Kefas Gimo]], [[Eric Forlee]] and [[Owen Maseko]].\n\nVilla Mangiacane in Tuscany hosts one of the largest modern collections of Shona Art sculptures in Europe with over 220 pieces on display across the Estate.\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Art of Zimbabwe}}\n{{reflist}}\n<!--Navigation box--><br />\n{{African topic|| art}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Art Of Zimbabwe}}\n[[Category:Zimbabwean art|*]]\n[[Category:Art by country|Zimbabwe]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Sculpture of Zimbabwe}}\n'''Zimbabwean [[art]]''' includes decorative [[esthetics]] applied to many aspects of life, including [[art object]]s as such, utilitarian objects, objects used in religion, warfare, in [[propaganda]], and in many other spheres. Within this broad arena, [[Zimbabwe]] has several identifiable categories of art. It is a hallmark of [[African culture]]s in general that art touches many aspects of life, and most tribes have a vigorous and often recognisable canon of styles and a great range of art-worked objects. These can include [[mask]]s, [[drum]]s, [[textile]] decoration, beadwork, carving, [[Sculpture of Zimbabwe|sculpture]], [[ceramic]] in various forms, housing and the person themselves. Decoration of the body in permanent ways such as [[scarification]] or [[tattoo]] or impermanently as in painting the body for a ceremony is a common feature of African cultures.\n\nSpoken or musical art is also a prominent part of Africas generally. Various instruments including drums, lamellophones and stringed bows have been used in Zimbabwe, while oratory, poetry, fable telling, praise singing and tribal ritual chants are also prominent.\n\nIn recent decades Zimbabwe has become widely recognized internationally for its [[Sculpture of Zimbabwe|sculpture]].\n\n==History==\nIt is useful to examine Zimbabwean art through time, by area, by main tribal division and as indicative of recent historic and political changes.\n\nThere is an artistic tradition in [[Zimbabwe]] that can be traced back to [[pottery]] of the [[Early Stone Age|Early]] and [[Late Stone Age]] and [[rock paintings]] from the Late Stone Age.<ref>Winter-Irving C. (1991) \"Visual Culture in Early History\", Chapter 8 in \"Stone Sculpture in Zimbabwe\", Roblaw Publishers, [[Harare]], {{ISBN|0908309147}}</ref> Many rock paintings produced by [[Bushmen|San]] artists between 10000 and 2000 years ago are found in cultural sites in Zimbabwe <ref>Garlake P S. (1993) \"Painted Caves: Prehistoric Art in Zimbabwe\", Modus Publications Pvt. Ltd, {{ISBN|0908309007}}</ref> and these demonstrate a high degree of skill in drawing. Many depict recognisable animal figures and use shading and colour to enhance the visual impact. The [[archaeology]] of Zimbabwe includes numerous pottery finds, which assist in the reconstruction of linguistic and cultural groupings within what is here termed [[Shona people|Shona]].<ref>Beach D N. (1980) \"Shona and Zimbabwe 900-1850: An Outline of Shona History\", Heinemann, {{ISBN|043594505X}}</ref> The pottery indicates that the people of the [[Late Iron Age]] were settled [[agriculturists]] and they have been categorised as forming groups such as the Harare culture and the Leopard\u2019s Kopje culture: the latter established in 980 AD in a site called K2.<ref>Huffman T. (1986) \"Iron Age Settlements and Origins of Class Distinction in Southern Africa\", Advances in World Archaeology, vol. 5, pp.291-338</ref> This group moved to [[Mapungubwe]] where they used stone walls to separate the ruling class from the rest of the population. This settlement was abandoned in the thirteenth century at around the time that a now much better-known site was developed by others who lived on the Zimbabwean plateau. This was [[Great Zimbabwe]], which dates from about 1250\u20131500 AD. It is a stone-walled town (''Zimbabwe'' means \"royal residence\") and shows evidence in its archaeology of skilled stone working: the walls were made of a local granite and no mortar was used in their construction.<ref>Needham D.E., Mashingaidze E.K, Bhebe N. (1984) \"From Iron Age to Independence, A History of Central Africa\", p17. Longman, England. {{ISBN|0582651115}}</ref> When excavated, [[Zimbabwe bird|six soapstone birds]] and a [[soapstone]] bowl were found in the eastern enclosure of the monument, so these [[Shona language|Shona-speaking]] Gumanye people certainly produced sculpture. Each object was carved from a single piece of stone and the birds have an aesthetic quality that places them as genuine \"art\". In comparing them to other better-known African stone sculpture, for example from the [[Yoruba people|Yoruba culture]], Philip Allison, writing in 1968, stated \"The stone sculptures of Rhodesia are few in number and of no great aesthetic distinction, but Zimbabwe itself has a place of peculiar importance in the study of African cultures\".<ref>Allison P., (1968) \"African Stone Sculpture\", p54. Lund Humphries, Great Britain</ref>\n\n===Stone Age===\nIn prehistory the area was widely settled by Kung peoples, the so-called [[Khoikhoi]] or San, Hottentot or Bushmen people, who were [[hunter gatherer]]s. They often lived in [[caves]] and made various artworks, including beading from shells for personal decoration, incising designs on [[ostrich]] shells and utilitarian objects such as clay water straws and also on the cave walls themselves. These dynamic and varied [[cave paintings]] date from around 10000 BCE and depict humans hunting many kinds of animals, warfare between humans, mystical and other unidentified marks, landscape and ceremonies where the humans are obviously decorated or in costume. The colours vary from black through brown, red, [[ochre]], yellow and white. The pigments used are unknown, though presumably contain a mix of local materials such as earth [[oxides]], fat, vegetable juices and possibly fluids from [[larva]]l insects. Certainly they have lasted for thousands of years.\n\nTheir descendants, who live mainly in Botswana and Namibia, sing a variety of uniquely structured and tuneful songs, accompanied sometimes by a plucked or struck bow. They also have a repertoire of dances, and there is no reason to suspect their ancestors did not do the same thing.\n\n===Iron Age===\nThese Stone Age people were supplanted by Iron Age [[Nguni people|Nguni]]-derived pastoral and farming peoples migrating in from the east and north around 2000 years ago, who became the ancestors of the [[Rozwi Empire|WaRozwi]]/Barotse people and by derivation the [[Amashona]] peoples. The art of these people can be seen in many decorated first-fired clay pots, where typically a repeated dhlo-dhlo (linear [[herringbone pattern|herringbone]]) [[Motif (visual arts)|motif]] or similar edging was applied. Other artwork is harder to source, though it can assumed they decorated the body and had [[beadwork]] and other art styles related to typical styles of the East and Central African Nguni peoples. A recurrent motif in Shona art is the transformation of a human into an animal of some kind.\n\n===Later prehistory===\nAt around the same time as the earlier incursions of these Bantu-type people (200BCE) there were sporadic expeditions by South-East coastal dwellers, probably by the Savi/Save river or over the Inyanga/[[Chimanimani]] mountain passes, into the Zimbabwe area to obtain [[gold]] for trade with [[Arab]] traders trading as far south as the mouth of the Savi. They built stone forts extending into the interior at one day's march from each other, with the final one being the complex now known as [[Great Zimbabwe]]. To service the coastal trade a town called [[Sofala]] was established at the  mouth of the Sofala river on the east coast. It had its heydey in around 700 AD/CE and served the [[Mwenemutapa]]/[[Monomotapa]] Kingdom, whose capital was [[Great Zimbabwe]]. Arabs took up residence in Sofala around 900AD/CE.\n\n===Early sculpture===\nArchaeology at Zimbabwe has shown several distinct phases of building and styles of stonework. It is likely the original complex was rather functional - essentially a [[fort]] and trading post only, and the later and more elaborate building occurred when the complex became the central administrative and royal centre of activity for the area. Some of the architectural features are probably linked with styles of coastal [[Swahili architecture]] and some are uniquely local. [[Chinese pottery]] shards, ivory, glass objects, local gold objects, Arabic and local beads, [[copper ingot]]s, [[iron]] ingots and other trade items have been found at Zimbabwe. The herringbone and other stepped linear forms of decoration in the walls are a feature of the most recent stonework. Similar stonework is seen at [[Khami]] ruins, a fort built on the way to Zimbabwe. However, the most impressive and unique feature of Zimbabwe are the huge [[soapstone birds]], the so-called [[Zimbabwe bird]]s, depicting a [[bird of prey]] perched on a zig-zag base motif. These birds are possibly based on the [[bateleur eagle]] or maybe a [[vulture]] species and might have had something to do with a [[Cult|religious cult]] or indicative of a [[totem]] animal for the ruling people at the time. Most of these sculptures are still in the country but one is in South Africa where it still adorns [[Groote Schuur]] an official residence, once the home of Cecil Rhodes. Another unexplained motif at Zimbabwe, which like the birds were mounted on the perimeter wall of the Great Enclosure, were stelae or tall narrow rectilinear pillars of rock (probably natural fracture artefacts) set at intervals round the top of the wall. The Zimbabwe bird is the most prominent motif of the current [[Zimbabwe flag]].\n\n===Amandebele incursions===\nThe origin of [[Amandebele]] speaking peoples in southern Zimbabwe received its main impetus from settlement around 1840 under Mzilikazi, a Khumalo chief who rebelled against Zulu rule. However, it is likely that such tribes began crossing the Limpopo sporadically from about 1800 onwards. Amandebele conflict with the Amashona drove them northwards into what was dubbed in colonial times Mashonaland. These [[Amandebele]]/[[Northern Ndebele people|Matabele]] peoples had several distinct art forms differing from the Amashona: in pottery styles, bead aprons and headpieces, house decoration, carving and decoration of war implements such as clubs/[[knobkierrie]]s and shields.\n\n===19th and early 20th century===\nArt in Zimbabwe lost most of its spiritual power with the conversion of the majority of the population to Christianity in the 19th and 20th centuries. Missionaries harmed the local cultures by demanding destruction of anything they regarded as anti-Christian, in particular masks or carvings thought to have votive powers, that is, to be appealing to some god that was not the Christian one. By the second world war most art objects produced in Zimbabwe were simply that: produced for tourist and local white settler consumption. With the advent of guns, animal skins prepared and decorated with small panels of other hides also began to appear more frequently in the early 20th century, as well as '[[kaross]]es' or fur blankets influenced by BaTchwana styles from Botswana to the south.\n\nAs for travelers to the area during the [[Victorian period]], they used art, especially painting, to depict some of what they saw there. This art of the [[colony|colonial period]] took landscape as its main theme and many of the European artists were present as part of expeditions that aimed to inform the public in Europe about life in Africa. For example, [[Thomas Baines]] joined the [[Zambezi]] expedition led by [[David Livingstone]] in 1858 and in 1861 he was one of the first to make oil paintings of [[Victoria Falls, Zambia|Victoria Falls]]. [[John Guille Millais]] spent six months of 1893 sketching and hunting in Zimbabwe.<ref name=CWI9>Winter-Irving C. (1991) \"Visual Arts since the Nineteenth Century\", Chapter 9 in \"Stone Sculpture in Zimbabwe\", Roblaw Publishers, [[Harare]], {{ISBN|0908309147}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1940s a Zimbabwe philanthropist named [[Jairos Jiri]] began to teach disabled people various artistic skills and centralised their production for sale in several outlets nationwide. These proved very popular and returned money to persons otherwise excluded from normal commercial activity. Jairos Jiri centres remain an important part of the artistic output in Zimbabwe. Typical items include tiles, tiled tables and wall plaques, basketwork, beading, carvings in wood and stone, jewellery and paintings.\n\n===Prelude to independence===\nIn the mid-1970s the nationalist guerilla incursions resulted in several atrocities against people in rural villages, including the sawing off of the upper lip of those perceived as collaborating with the government forces. The white government collated photographic images and a text list of these events into a propaganda booklet called 'Anatomy of Terror'. This was designed to show the brutality of the nationalists against innocent rural native people. Images from this publication are today to be found on [[YouTube]] (for example under 'Terrorists in the Rhodesian bush').\n\nOther art from the white minority during the civil \"Rhodesian Bush\" (1968 - 1979) war consisted mainly of depictions of indigenous fauna and flora and landscapes. These subjects had always been popular and remain popular to this day among white artists. No individual white artist expressed any significant political sentiment during the civil war era. However, many film, still and sound clips celebrating the government forces' role during this time are currently available on YouTube.\n\n===Painting in the 20th century===\nWhile there were many well-known white artists in Rhodesia prior to independence in 1980, there were relatively few black artists of note. One of these was [[Kingsley Sambo]] (1932\u20131977), who started to paint at the [[Cyrene Mission]] where Canon Edward Paterson taught art. Two of Sambo\u2019s paintings are in the [[Museum of Modern Art in New York|MoMA]]. Others were [[Thomas Mukarobgwa]] (also a leading sculptor) and [[Joseph Ndandarika]] <ref>Zilberg J. (2006) [http://www.nationalgallery.co.zw/PDFs/Kinglsey%20Sambo%20and%20Vincent%20Van%20Gogh.pdf]{{dead link|date=July 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} National Gallery archive</ref>\n\nAlthough the Workshop School of the National Gallery supported and encouraged painters from 1957, Rhodesia had few Colleges for Fine Arts. The Bulawayo College of Fine Art and Design trained artists in fine art and graphic design for Rhodesian industry and it was not until 1963 that Alex Lambert set up the [[Mzilikazi Art School]] in [[Bulawayo]] specifically to encourage local people to take up art.\n\nThe [[National Gallery of Zimbabwe|National Gallery]] has, since 1986, promoted local artists by hosting an annual exhibition of contemporary visual arts called \"Zimbabwe Heritage\". Patronage from Zimbabwean companies \u2013 the Baringa Corporation (for paintings, graphics, textiles, ceramics and photograph) and the Nedlaw Investment and Trust Corporation (for sculpture) \u2013 initially supported the expense of having an international panel of judges come to Zimbabwe to assess the works and make Awards. Later, the sponsorship of the event grew to include international companies such as [[Mobil]], [[Lever Brothers]], [[The BOC Group]] and [[Longman]]. Early winners of Awards of Distinction in the painters and graphics category included Berry Bickle (1987), Bert Hemsteede (1988), Rashid Jogee (1992) and Tichaona Madzamba (1992).<ref name=NGZ>See annual catalogues for ''Zimbabwe Heritage'', produced by the [[National Gallery of Zimbabwe|National Gallery]]</ref>\n\nPainters who have established reputations in post-independence Zimbabwe include [[Dumisani Ngwenya]], [[Taylor Nkomo]] and [[Richard Jack]].<ref name=CWI9/>\n\n===Sculpture in the 20th and 21st centuries===\n[[File:Zimbabwe sculpture at Atlanta airport.JPG|thumb|''[[Zimbabwe Sculpture: a Tradition in Stone]]'', [[Atlanta]], United States, at [[Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport]] between concourses T and A]]\n\n{{Main|Sculpture of Zimbabwe}}\n[[Chapungu Sculpture Park]] in [[Harare]] is currently an important locality for display of (mainly) Shona sculptors and carvers. Another [http://www.chapungusculpturepark.com Chapungu Sculpture Park] was created in 2007 in the United States, along with a gallery, in Loveland, Colorado. ''[[Zimbabwe Sculpture: a Tradition in Stone]]'' is on permanent display at [[Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport|Atlanta's airport]].\n\n[[AVAC Arts]] URL [[www.avacarts.com]] is another vital pace-setting player in the Zimbabwe contemporary arts sector promoting adaptation and utilization of new technologies and runs an online portal facilitating international art trade and promotion of Zimbabwean stone sculptures.\n\nSince antiquity local artists have been using the steatite/[[soapstone]] deposits of the eastern Zimbabwe mountain ranges to produce artworks showing, among other things, the common Shona theme of animal/human inter-morphosis. These works became much larger under the patronage of white collectors in the 1960s (though the Zimbabwe birds of antiquity are massive) and now it is common to see monumental soapstone sculptures both nationally and internationally.\n\nNoted Zimbabwean artists include sculptor [[Patrick Mavros]], and painters [[Kim Donaldson]], [[Larry Norton]], [[Brennan Seward]], [[Kefas Gimo]], [[Eric Forlee]] and [[Owen Maseko]].\n\nVilla Mangiacane in Tuscany hosts one of the largest modern collections of Shona Art sculptures in Europe with over 220 pieces on display across the Estate.\n\n==References==\n{{commons category|Art of Zimbabwe}}\n{{reflist}}\n<!--Navigation box--><br />\n{{African topic|| art}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Art Of Zimbabwe}}\n[[Category:Zimbabwean art|*]]\n[[Category:Art by country|Zimbabwe]]\n", "name_user": "Tom Radulovich", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLater prehistory:links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zimbabwean_art"}
{"title_page": "Saw (franchise)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:''Saw'' (franchise)}}\n{{Infobox media franchise\n| title = ''Saw''\n| image = Saw film logo.png\n| imagesize = 210\n| caption = Official franchise logo\n| creator = [[James Wan]]<br />[[Leigh Whannell]]\n| owner = [[Lions Gate Entertainment]]\n| origin = ''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'' (2003)\n| comics = * ''[[Saw: Rebirth]]'' (2005)\n| films = * ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Saw II]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Saw III]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Saw IV]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Saw V]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Saw VI]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Saw 3D]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]'' (2020)\n| shorts = * ''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'' (2003)\n* ''Full Disclosure Report: Piecing Together Jigsaw'' (2005)\n* ''The Scott Tibbs Documentary'' (2006)\n| vgs = * ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'' (2010)\n| radio = \n| soundtracks = * ''[[Saw (soundtrack)|Saw]]''\n* ''[[Saw II (soundtrack)|Saw II]]''\n* ''[[Saw III (soundtrack)|Saw III]]''\n* ''[[Saw IV (soundtrack)|Saw IV]]'' \n* ''[[Saw V (soundtrack)|Saw V]]'' \n* ''[[Saw VI (soundtrack)|Saw VI]]'' \n* ''[[Saw 3D (Original Score Soundtrack)|Saw 3D]]'' \n* ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)#Music|Jigsaw]]''\n| music = * \"[[Hello Zepp]]\"\n| otherlabel1 = Theme park ride(s)\n| otherdata1 = * [[Saw \u2013 The Ride]]\n| otherlabel2 = Haunted attraction(s)\n| otherdata2 = * Game Over<ref name=\"gover\">{{Cite web|url=https://lasvegassun.com/news/2009/oct/12/sprawling-21st-century-freak-show/|title=Fright Dome: Circus Circus fear factory teems with terrific human horrors - Las Vegas Sun Newspaper|first=Joe|last=Brown|date=October 12, 2009|website=lasvegassun.com}}</ref>\n* Jigsaw's Revenge<ref name=\"gover\" />\n* Saw: Game Over<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3172917/a-bd-walkthrough-of-saw-game-over-jigsaw-s-horror-nights-maze/|title=A BD Walkthrough of \u2018Saw: Game Over\u2019, Jigsaw\u2019s Horror Nights Maze!|first=Bloody Disgusting|last=Staff|date=August 19, 2009}}</ref>\n* Saw: Game On<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://worldofpopculture.com/vampyrecastle-of-the-undead-added-to-halloween-horror-nights-2010/|title='Vampyre:Castle of the Undead' Added to Halloween Horror Nights 2010!|first=Kristyn|last=Clarke|date=September 16, 2010}}</ref>\n* Saw Maze<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.parkz.com.au/update/2010/10/28/254-Warner_Bros_Movie_World_Halloween_2010.html|title=The Parkz Update: Warner Bros. Movie World, Halloween 2010|website=Parkz}}</ref>\n* Saw: The Games of Jigsaw<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2017/08/14/universal-studios-saw-the-games-of-jigsaw-to-set-new-traps-for-guests-during-halloween-horror-nights/|title=Universal Studios\u2019 \u2018SAW: The Games of Jigsaw\u2019 to set new traps for guests during Halloween Horror Nights|date=August 14, 2017}}</ref>\n* Saw: Alive<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thorpepark.com/fright-nights/saw-alive|title=SAW: Alive - Live Action Horror Maze &#124; Thorpe Park|website=www.thorpepark.com}}</ref>\n* Jigsaw: Survive the Trap<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ew.com/movies/2017/09/27/saw-jigsaw-escape-room-new-york-comic-con/|title='Jigsaw'-themed escape room to trap 'Saw' fans at New York Comic Con|website=EW.com}}</ref>\n* Saw Escape Room<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://attractionsmagazine.com/saw-escape-room-opens-in-las-vegas/|title=Official 'Saw' escape room now open in Las Vegas|date=January 16, 2018}}</ref>\n| otherlabel3 = Fan film(s) universe\n| otherdata3 = * ''Saw: Heritage'' (2016)\n* ''He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw'' (2020)\n* ''Saw: Bloodlines'' (2021)\n}}\n\n'''''Saw''''' is an American [[horror film|horror]] [[media franchise|franchise]] created by [[James Wan]] and [[Leigh Whannell]]. It consists of eight [[feature film]]s and additional media.\n\nIn 2003, Wan and Whannell made a [[Saw (2003 film)|short film]] to help [[Sales presentation|pitch]] a potential [[feature film]] concept. Their pitch was ultimately successful, and in 2004, [[Saw (2004 film)|the first installment]] of what would become the feature film franchise debuted at the [[Sundance Film Festival]]. The film was released theatrically that October, by [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate]]. The sequels were directed by [[Darren Lynn Bousman]], [[David Hackl]], and [[Kevin Greutert]], and were written by Wan, Whannell, Bousman, [[Patrick Melton]], and [[Marcus Dunstan]], and were released subsequently every October, on the Friday before [[Halloween]], between 2004 and 2010. Both of the creators remained with the franchise as [[executive producer]]s.\n\nOn July 22, 2010, producer [[Mark Burg]] confirmed that the seventh film, ''[[Saw 3D]]'', is the final installment of the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bowles|first=Scott|date=July 22, 2010|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2010-07-22-saw22_ST_N.htm|title='Saw 3D' will be the final cut for horror franchise|work=[[USA Today]]|access-date=July 22, 2010|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61r3dlvkb|archive-date=September 20, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, Lionsgate reportedly expressed interest in continuing the franchise with a [[Reboot (fiction)|reboot]].<ref name=\"Lionsgate Remaking Saw\">{{cite web|title=Lionsgate Remaking Saw?|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/58024/lionsgate-remaking-saw|publisher=DreadCentral}}</ref> In November 2013, it was reported that they were actively developing a sequel.<ref name=\"bloody-disgusting.com\">{{cite web|title=Exclusive: Lionsgate Is Actively Developing Next 'Saw'|url=http://bloody-disgusting.com/news/3262916/exclusive-lionsgate-is-actively-developing-next-saw/|publisher=Bloody Disgusting}}</ref> An eighth film, ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]'', was eventually released in October 2017. In 2019, a ninth film was announced, ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]'', with comedian and actor [[Chris Rock]] attached to star, produce, and co-write.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3561412/saw-reimagined-chris-rock-darren-bousman-returning-direct/|title=\u2018SAW\u2019 Being Reimagined by Chris Rock with Darren Bousman Returning to Direct!|first=Brad|last=Miska|website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise primarily revolves around [[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer]], also called the \"Jigsaw Killer\" or simply \"Jigsaw\". He was introduced briefly in ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' and developed in more detail in ''[[Saw II]]'' and the subsequent films. Rather than killing his [[List of Saw characters|victims]] outright, Jigsaw traps them in situations that he calls \"tests\" or \"games\" to test their will to live through physical or psychological torture and believes that if they survive, they will be \"rehabilitated\". Despite the fact that John was murdered in ''[[Saw III]]'', the films continue to focus on the posthumous influence of the Jigsaw Killer and his apprentices by exploring his character via [[Flashback (narrative)|flashbacks]].\n\nThe franchise grossed more than {{US$|1 billion|long=no|link=yes}} from [[box office]] and retail sales by 2009,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lidz|first=Franz|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/25/movies/25lidz.html?_r=1&pagewanted=2&hpw|title=Limbs Pile Up, and Money, Too|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=October 21, 2009|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> and the films have collectively grossed over {{US$|976 million|long=no}} at the worldwide box office as of 2018. The film series as a whole has received mostly mixed to negative reviews by critics, but has been a financial success at the box office and is one of the highest-grossing horror film franchises of all time. While the films have been classified as [[Splatter film#Torture porn|torture porn]] by some critics,<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Sharrett|first=Christopher|title=The Problem of Saw: \"Torture Porn\" and the Conservatism of Contemporary Horror Films|magazine=[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]]|number=1|volume=35|date=December 2009|pages=32\u201337 |jstor= 41690851 |url=https://baixardoc.com/preview/the-problem-of-saw-torture-porn-horror-films-irony-5cf03d786626c |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016013623/https://baixardoc.com/preview/the-problem-of-saw-torture-porn-horror-films-irony-5cf03d786626c |archivedate= 2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.variety.com/review/VE1117941442 | last=Nelson|first=Rob| title=Saw VI Movie Review | work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | publisher=[[Reed Business Information]] | date=October 23, 2009 | access-date=December 8, 2009| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5n3nfI0IX | archive-date=January 25, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/saw-vi-film-review-93699|title=Saw VI \u2013 Film Review|last=Scheck|first=Frank|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]] |date=October 23, 2009|access-date=September 15, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/61jQpk10a|archive-date=September 15, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> the creators of ''Saw'' disagree with that term.<ref name=\"AVClub\">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/articles/saw-creators-leigh-whannell-and-james-wan,46975/|title=Saw creators Leigh Whannell and James Wan|last=Tobias|first=Scott|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|publisher=[[The Onion]]|date=October 29, 2010|access-date=August 16, 2011|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/60zpLcBgr|archive-date=August 16, 2011| url-status= live}}</ref>\n{{toc limit|3}}\n\n==Films==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=100%\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | U.S. release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Screenwriter(s) \n! scope=\"col\" | Story by\n! scope=\"col\" width=15%| Producer(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2004|10|29}}\n| [[James Wan]]\n| [[Leigh Whannell]]\n| James Wan and Leigh Whannell\n| rowspan=\"8\"| [[Gregg Hoffman]], [[Oren Koules]] and [[Mark Burg]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw II]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2005|10|28}}\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Darren Lynn Bousman]]\n| colspan=\"2\" | Leigh Whannell and Darren Lynn Bousman\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw III]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2006|10|27}}\n| Leigh Whannell\n| Leigh Whannell and James Wan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2007|10|26}}\n| [[Patrick Melton]] & [[Marcus Dunstan]]\n| Patrick Melton & Marcus Dunstan and [[Thomas Fenton]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw V]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2008|10|24}}\n| [[David Hackl]]\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"3\"| Patrick Melton & Marcus Dunstan\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2009|10|23}}\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Kevin Greutert]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2010|10|29}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2017|10|27}}\n| [[The Spierig Brothers|Michael and Peter Spierig]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Josh Stolberg]] & Peter Goldfinger\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:left\" | ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Start date|2020|}}\n| Darren Lynn Bousman\n| Josh Stolberg & Peter Goldfinger\n| [[Chris Rock]]\n| Oren Koules and Mark Burg\n|}\n\n===Future===\n{{Main|Spiral (2020 film)}}\nIn May 2019, it was confirmed that a ninth film in the series was in production.  Former series director [[Darren Lynn Bousman]] will return to helm the film. Comedian and actor [[Chris Rock]] will star in the film and will also be involved as an executive producer, in addition to writing the story treatment. Rock stated \"I've been a fan of ''Saw'' since the first film in 2004. I am excited by the opportunity to take this to a really intense and twisted new place\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/05/chris-rock-to-reboot-saw-franchise-with-lionsgate-twisted-pictures-1202616185/|title=Chris Rock To Reboot \u2018Saw\u2019 Franchise With Lionsgate & Twisted Pictures|first1=Anthony|last1=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref> ''Jigsaw'' writers Josh Stolberg and Pete Goldfinger are returning to write the screenplay. Stolberg later clarified that ninth installment will exist in the same continuity of the previous films, though it will not be a direct sequel to ''Jigsaw''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/1143993966049685504|title=The film is NOT a reboot. It is canon. All the films exist in the same universe. And who knows, maybe Saw X will tie all the stories together. You never know.|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=June 26, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/joshstolberg/status/1143028357610627073|title=I can say with pretty much certainly that our new film will NOT be called Jigsaw 2. But I don't make the decisions, so who knows. But it's NOT a sequel to Jigsaw. It's DEFINITELY in the timeline of ALL the films though.|first=Josh|last=Stolberg|date=June 23, 2019|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe movie began filming in June 2019 and was scheduled to be released in theaters on May 15, 2020,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.businesstimes.cn/articles/112615/20190524/saw-9-release-date-spoilers-chris-rock-reboot-might-introduce-creepy-new-john-kramer.htm|title='Saw 9' Release Date, Spoilers: Chris Rock Reboot Might Introduce Creepy New John Kramer|first=Business|last=Times|date=May 24, 2019|website=Business Times|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/saw-9-movie-filming-start/|title=New Saw Movie Set To Start Filming This Month|date=June 27, 2019|website=ScreenRant|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref> but was delayed due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/new-saw-movie-spiral-antebellum-release-date-delayed-coronavirus/ |title=Lionsgate Delays Chris Rock's 'Saw' Movie, Janelle Monae's 'Antebellum' |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |first=Jeff |last=Sneider |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Short film===\n''[[Saw (2003 film)|Saw]]'', retrospectively referred to as ''Saw 0.5'', is a 2003 [[short film]] that served as a promotional tool in pitching the film's potential to [[Lionsgate]], included on the second disc of the uncut DVD release of ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'', released by itself, and on the ''Saw Trilogy'' DVD containing ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]'' Uncut Edition, ''[[Saw II]]'' Special Edition, and ''[[Saw III]]'' Director's Cut, packaged with a limited-edition 3D puppet head box version of [[Billy the Puppet]].\n\n==Cast and crew==\n===Cast===\n{{Details|List of Saw (franchise) cast members|List of Saw (franchise) characters|topic=the cast and characters}}\n\n{{Cast indicator|S|V|C|A}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\" width=99%\n!rowspan=\"3\" width=\"14%\" | Character\n!colspan=\"9\" | Films\n|-\n! ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n! ''[[Saw II]]''\n! ''[[Saw III]]''\n! ''[[Saw IV]]''\n! ''[[Saw V]]''\n! ''[[Saw VI]]''\n! ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n! ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n! ''[[Spiral (2020 film)|Spiral:<br>{{small|From the<br>Book of Saw}}]]''\n|-\n|{{small|'''2004'''}}\n|{{small|'''2005'''}}\n|{{small|'''2006'''}}\n|{{small|'''2007'''}}\n|{{small|'''2008'''}}\n|{{small|'''2009'''}}\n|{{small|'''2010'''}}\n|{{small|'''2017'''}}\n|{{small|'''2020'''}}\n|-\n![[Jigsaw (Saw character)|John Kramer<br />{{small|Jigsaw}}]]\n|colspan=\"8\" | [[Tobin Bell]]