D from the Set of 'Saw VII 3D' | work=[[Bloody Disgusting]] | publisher= The Collective | last= Miska|first= Brad | date=February 15, 2010 | access-date=February 16, 2010 | quote=At this point I view it as getting paid to go through a $17 million dollar one-man 3D film school program, so how's that for looking at the bright side of a dark situation?| archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5namYxahq | archive-date=February 16, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n|{{start date|2017|10|27}}\n|$38,052,832\n|$64,900,056\n|$102,952,888\n|align=\"center\" |$10 million\n|align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"JigsawBOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=saw2017.htm|title=Jigsaw (2017)|work=Box Office Mojo|publisher=Amazon.com|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n!colspan=2 align=\"center\"|Total\n!$453,966,900\n!$522,305,866\n!$976,272,768\n!align=\"center\" |$77 million\n!\n|}\n\n===Critical and public response===\nOn [[IGN]]'s list of the top twenty-five film franchises of all time, the ''Saw'' series ranked as 25th.<ref>{{cite web|date=2006-11-20|url=http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746875p1.html|title=IGN: Top 25 Movie Franchises of All Time: #25|work=[[IGN]] |url-status=dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061202074915/http://movies.ign.com/articles/746/746875p1.html |archive-date= 2006-12-02 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\"\n! align=\"center\" | '''Film'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[Rotten Tomatoes]]'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[Metacritic]]'''\n! align=\"center\" | '''[[CinemaScore]]'''\n|-\n|-\n| ''[[Saw (2004 film)|Saw]]''\n| 49% (184 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw/|title=Saw|work=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango Media]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 46 (32 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw/critic-reviews|title=Saw (2004): Reviews|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| C+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\">{{cite web | title = CinemaScore | url = https://www.cinemascore.com/publicsearch/index/title/ | website = [[CinemaScore]] }}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Saw II]]''\n| 37% (122 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_ii/|title=Saw II|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 40 (28 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-ii/critic-reviews|title=Saw II (2005): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B+<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw III]]''\n| 28% (92 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_3/|title=Saw III|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| 48 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iii/critic-reviews|title=Saw III (2006): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw IV]]''\n| 20% (81 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_4/|title=Saw IV|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| 36 (16 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-iv/critic-reviews|title=Saw IV (2007): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=January 4, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw V]]''\n| 13% (76 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_v/|title=Saw V|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n| 20 (13 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-v/critic-reviews|title=Saw V (2008): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=November 15, 2008}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|C<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw VI]]''\n| 39% (72 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw_VI/|title=Saw VI|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=July 11, 2010}}</ref>\n| 30 (12 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-vi/critic-reviews|title=Saw VI (2009): Reviews|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 24, 2009}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Saw 3D]]''\n| 10% (79 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://us.rottentomatoes.com/m/saw3d/|title=Saw 3D|work=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Flixster|access-date=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n| 24 (17 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/saw-3d/critic-reviews|title=Critic Reviews for Saw 3D (2010)|work=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B\u2013<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|-\n| ''[[Jigsaw (2017 film)|Jigsaw]]''\n| 33% (87 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw (2017)|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/jigsaw_2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes|publisher=Fandango Media|access-date=July 5, 2019}}</ref>\n| 39 (18 reviews)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jigsaw Reviews|url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/jigsaw|website=Metacritic|publisher=CBS Interactive|access-date=October 29, 2017}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"|B<ref name=\"CinemaScore\" />\n|}\n\n==Other media==\n{{main|List of Saw media}}\n\n===Video games===\n[[Japan]]ese video game company [[Konami]] currently owns the rights to the ''Saw'' interactive video game property. Konami stated in mid-2009 that they wanted to make ''Saw'' a series of video games to supplement the films. They also wish to make ''Saw'' their next big survival horror franchise next to their other property, ''[[Silent Hill]]''. They stated that because ''Saw'' focuses on visual intensity and ''Silent Hill'' focuses on psychological terror, both could exist in the video game industry without directly competing against each other.<ref name= \"Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?\">{{cite news|url=http://weblogs.variety.com/the_cut_scene/2009/04/silent-hill-say-hello-to-your-new-brother-jigsawkonami-has-confirmed-an-earlier-cut-scene-report-that-it-has-bought-the-pub.html|title=Will Saw Be Konami's Second Great Horror Franchise?|work=The Cut Scene|date=2009-04-02|access-date=2009-08-04}}</ref>\n\nThe first game in the series, ''[[Saw (video game)|Saw]]'', set between the first and second film in the series, was initially released on October 6, 2009.<ref name=WanWhannell>{{Cite web|url=http://www.360-hq.com/article-2382-thread-1-0.html|title=Producer James Wan On Saw The Video Game &#124; 360-HQ.COM|website=www.360-hq.com|accessdate=October 7, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Nick|last=Wingfield|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB118092768266523504 |title=A Start Up's Risky Niche: Movie-Based Videogames|date=2007-06-04|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=2008-01-30|url=http://xbox360.ign.com/articles/848/848533p1.html|title=Saw announced|access-date=2008-01-30}}</ref> with a sequel ''[[Saw II: Flesh & Blood]]'', released on October 19, 2010, for the Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3, ten days before the release of the seventh film, ''Saw 3D''.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/57520/Jigsaw_Returns.php|title=Jigsaw Returns!|publisher=[[Gamasutra]]|date=April 9, 2010|access-date=April 9, 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[David Tapp]] and [[Amanda Young]] were released as part of the downloadable ''Saw Chapter'' for the video game ''[[Dead by Daylight]]''.<ref name= \"Dead by Daylight\">{{cite web|url=http://comicbook.com/gaming/2018/01/22/dead-by-daylight-saw-dlc-confirmed-jigsaw-coming-tomorrow/|publisher=Comic Book|title=Dead By Daylight Confirms Saw DLC, Releasing Tomorrow|date=2018-01-22|access-date=2018-01-22}}</ref>\n\n===Comic books===\n''Saw: Rebirth'', a [[comic book]] prequel to the original film released to promote ''Saw II''. Its [[canon (fiction)|canonicity]] was later contradicted by events in ''Saw IV''. It is, however, the first canonical appearance of Jigsaw's wife, Jill, who was later introduced into the film series in ''Saw III'', and established still-canonical elements of Jigsaw's backstory (an engineer who is dying from brain cancer.)\n\n===Theme park attractions===\n* \"[[Saw: The Ride]]\" is a [[Gerstlauer Euro-Fighter]] roller coaster themed around the franchise, which opened on March 13, 2009, at [[Thorpe Park]] in the [[United Kingdom]]. It features an enclosed dark ride section with special effects, before cars travel outside and are pulled up a 100-foot vertical lift hill into a steep 100-degree drop.\n* [[Thorpe Park]] opened a temporary ''Saw'' attraction called \"Saw \u2014 Movie Bites\" for their 2009 Fright Nights event.\n* It was announced in October 2009 that Thorpe Park would also be adding a permanent, year-round [[live action]] horror [[maze]] themed around the ''Saw'' movies. It opened at the start of the 2010 season, and features six scenes representing one iconic trap from each movie to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hauntedattractions.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=570&Itemid=2|title=Thorpe: SAW Alive exclusive details|work=Haunted Attractions|publisher=hauntedattractions.co.uk|access-date=2009-11-29}}</ref>\n* \"[[Halloween Horror Nights|Saw: Game Over]]\" was a 2009 maze made by [[Universal Parks & Resorts|Universal Studios]] for [[Halloween Horror Nights]], based on characters, traps and scenes from the films.<ref name= \"Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shocktillyoudrop.com/news/topnews.php?id=11469|publisher=Shock Till You Drop|title=Sneek Peak At Universal's Saw: Game Over Maze!|date=2009-08-19|access-date=2009-11-12}}</ref> At the [[Universal Studios Hollywood]] rendition of Horror Nights it was titled ''Saw: Game Over'', while at the [[Universal Studios Florida]] rendition, it was simply titled ''Saw''.\n* \"Saw\", a themed haunted house, operated during the month of October at [http://www.frightdome.com Fright Dome], [[Circus Circus Las Vegas]]. It featured interactive, handcrafted replicas of the \"games\" set by [[Jigsaw Killer|Jigsaw]]. It was introduced in 2009 and partnered with [[Lionsgate]] and [[Twisted Pictures]].\n* In 2010, \"[[Halloween Fright Nights]]\" at [[Warner Bros. Movie World]] featured a maze created by [[Sudden Impact Entertainment]], featuring characters, traps and scenes from the films. The maze was simply titled \"Saw Maze\".\n* \"Saw Haunted Attraction\" was a maze at the Brea Plaza Shopping Center in 2008 created by Sinister Pointe Haunted Attractions.\n* \"SAWMANIA\" was a fan event in New York. Eventgoers were able to meet actors and directors, and view props used in the films.\n\n=== Fan films universe ===\nThe impact of the ''Saw'' films inspired creators from all over the world to create [[fan film]]s based on the franchise. The films are in no way affiliated with [[Lionsgate Films|Lionsgate films]] or [[Twisted Pictures]]. On October 31, 2016, Christos Arfanis, released ''Saw: Heritage''.<ref>{{Citation|title=SAW: Heritage|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt6093012/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> The film has received mixed ratings.\n\nIn the next few years, more projects are set to be released. Arfranis returns to helm another film, ''He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw''<ref>{{Citation|title=He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11915184/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> and SAW House will produce their first film,  ''Saw: Bloodlines'', directed by Thaine Tobio in his debut and featuring writing from Alen Alic and Thomas Claxton.<ref>{{Citation|title=Saw: Bloodlines|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11323584/|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/r/saw/comments/b5k3g3/what_is_saw_bloodlines/|title=r/saw - What is saw bloodlines?|website=reddit|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=\"99%\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n! scope=\"col\" | U.S. release date\n! scope=\"col\" | Director(s)\n! scope=\"col\" width=15% | Screenwriter(s) \n! scope=\"col\" | Story by\n! scope=\"col\" width=15% | Producer(s)\n|-\n|-\n| Saw: Heritage\n| October 31, 2016\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Arfanis\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Afranis\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Afranis\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Afranis\n|-\n| He Helped Me: A Fan Film from the Book of Saw\n| 2020\n| align=\"center\" | Jay Anthony Gonato and Michael Welch\n| align=\"center\" | France Cuiz, Alex Rieger, Tymetreus Thompson, Kiriakos Vilchez and Michael Welch\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Arfanis\n| align=\"center\" | Christos Arfanis\n|-\n| Saw: Bloodlines\n| 2021\n| align=\"center\" | Thaine Tobio\n| align=\"center\" | Alen Alic and Thomas Claxton\n| align=\"center\" | Robert M. Clarke and Thaine Tobio\n| align=\"center\" | Luke Hadland\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Film|Speculative fiction/Horror}}\n* [[Splatter film]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Saw (franchise)}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n; Databases\n* [http://allmovie.com/work/saw-film-series-356901 ''Saw'' film series] at [[Allmovie]]\n* [http://www.boxofficemojo.com/franchises/chart/?id=Saw.htm ''Saw'' film series] at [[Box Office Mojo]]\n; Official sites\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041126235053/http://www.sawmovie.com/ ''Saw'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071002065430/http://www.saw2.com/ ''Saw II'' website] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061116073244/http://saw3.com/ ''Saw III website''] (archive)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071024161726/http://movies.break.com/saw4/ ''Saw IV'' website] (archive)\n* [http://www.saw5.com ''Saw V'' website]\n; Other links\n* [http://www.thorpepark.com/ Thorpe Park] - home to two ''Saw'' attractions\n* [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/scott-mendelson/goodbye-john-a-farewell-t_b_775552.html?view=print Goodbye John: A Farewell to Saw, as Jigsaw Lays His Last Trap] by Scott Mendelson\n\n{{Saw}}\n\n[[Category:Film franchises introduced in 2004]]\n[[Category:Horror film franchises]]\n[[Category:Splatter films]]\n[[Category:American serial killer films]]\n[[Category:American teen horror films]]\n[[Category:Saw (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Lions Gate franchises]]\n[[Category:Films about mass murder]]\n[[Category:American splatter films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into comics]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into video games]]\n", "name_user": "FanFilmsMaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFan films universe:Source: https://www.imdb.com/title/tt11915184/ Added Thomas Claxton and Christos Arfanis as directors of He Helped Me.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saw_(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "Outline of Zimbabwe", "text_new": "{{See also|Index of Zimbabwe-related articles}}\n{{Short description|1=Overview of and topical guide to Zimbabwe}}\n<!--... Attention:  THIS IS AN OUTLINE\n\n        part of the set of 740+ outlines listed at\n             [[Portal:Contents/Outlines]].\n\n                 Wikipedia outlines are\n              a special type of list article.\n              They make up one of Wikipedia's\n                content navigation systems\n\n                See [[Wikipedia:Outlines]]\n                      for more details.\n                   Further improvements\n              to this outline are on the way\n...-->\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Flag of Zimbabwe.svg\n| width1 = 214\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = The [[Flag of Zimbabwe]]\n| image2 = Coat of Arms of Zimbabwe.svg\n| width2 = 122\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = The [[Coat of arms of Zimbabwe]]\n| footer = \n}}\n[[Image:LocationZimbabwe.svg|thumb|The location of [[Zimbabwe]]]]\n\nThe following [[Outline (list)|outline]] is provided as an overview of and topical guide to Zimbabwe:\n\n'''[[Zimbabwe]]''' &ndash; [[Landlocked country|landlocked]] [[List of sovereign states|sovereign country]] located in [[Southern Africa]], between the [[Zambezi River]] and [[Limpopo River]].<ref name=CIA_World_Factbook>{{cite web|date=July 3, 2009|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/zi.html|title=Zimbabwe|work=[[The World Factbook]]|publisher=[[United States]] [[Central Intelligence Agency]]|accessdate=July 23, 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|limit=5}}\n\n==General reference==\n[[Image:Zimbabwe-CIA WFB Map.png|thumb|An enlargeable basic map of [[Zimbabwe]]]]\n* [[International Phonetic Alphabet|Pronunciation]]: {{IPAc-en|z|\u026a|m|\u02c8|b|\u0251\u02d0|b|w|e\u026a}}\n* Common English country name:  [[Zimbabwe]]\n* Official English country name:  The [[Republic of Zimbabwe]]\n* Common [[endonym]](s): [[List of countries and capitals in native languages| ]]\n* Official endonym(s): [[List of official endonyms of present-day nations and states| ]]\n* [[List of adjectival and demonymic forms of place names#Countries and nations|Adjectival]](s): [[Zimbabwean]] <!-- This disambiguation page is the only page on Wikipedia that specifically explains this term and its country adjectival contexts, and it does so excellently.  Please leave this link in place. -->\n* [[List of adjectival and demonymic forms of place names#Countries and nations|Demonym]](s):\n* [[Etymology]]: [[Name of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[International rankings of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[ISO country codes]]:  ZW, ZWE, 716\n* [[ISO region codes]]:  See [[ISO 3166-2:ZW]]\n* [[Internet]] [[country code top-level domain]]:  [[.zw]]\n\n==Geography of Zimbabwe==\n[[Image:Zimbabwe Topography.png|thumb|An enlargeable topographic map of [[Zimbabwe]]]]\n\n[[Geography of Zimbabwe]]\n* Zimbabwe is: a [[landlocked country]]\n* Location:\n** [[Eastern Hemisphere]] and [[Southern Hemisphere]]\n** [[Africa]]\n*** [[East Africa]]\n*** [[Southern Africa]]\n** [[Time zone]]:  [[Central Africa Time]] ([[UTC+02]])\n** Extreme points of Zimbabwe\n*** High:  [[Mount Nyangani]] {{convert|2592|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n*** Low:  [[Confluence]] of [[Runde River]] and [[Save River (Africa)|Save River]] {{convert|162|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n** Land boundaries:  3,066&nbsp;km\n::{{Flag|Mozambique}} 1,231 km\n::{{Flag|Botswana}} 813 km\n::{{Flag|Zambia}} 797 km\n::{{Flag|South Africa}} 225 km\n:* Coastline:  ''none''\n* [[Place names in Zimbabwe]]\n* Population: 11,392,000 people (2009 [[Approximation|estimate]]) - [[List of countries by population|73rd most populous country]]\n* Area:  {{convert|390580|km2|abbr=on}} - [[List of countries and outlying territories by total area|60th largest country]]\n* [[:commons:Atlas of Zimbabwe|Atlas of Zimbabwe]]\n\n===Environment of Zimbabwe===\n[[Image:Satellite image of Zimbabwe in December 2002.jpg|thumb|An enlargeable satellite image of [[Zimbabwe]]]]\n* [[Climate of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[List of ecoregions in Zimbabwe|Ecoregions in Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Renewable energy in Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Geology of Zimbabwe]]\n* Protected areas of Zimbabwe\n** [[List of national parks of Zimbabwe|National parks of Zimbabwe]]\n** [[Zimbabwe Parks and Wildlife Estate]]\n* [[Wildlife of Zimbabwe]]\n** Fauna of Zimbabwe\n*** [[List of birds of Zimbabwe|Birds of Zimbabwe]]\n*** [[List of mammals of Zimbabwe|Mammals of Zimbabwe]]\n\n====Natural geographic features of Zimbabwe====\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:Zambezi River near Zambezi Town.jpg|thumb|Zambezi River in North Western Zambia {{Deletable image-caption|Friday, May 22 2009}}]] -->\n{{Main|List of landforms of Zimbabwe|Landforms of Zimbabwe}}\n\n* Glaciers in Zimbabwe: none <ref>The only [[List of glaciers in Africa|glaciers in Africa]] are on Mt Kenya (in Kenya), on Kilimanjaro (in Tanzania), and in the Ruwenzori Mountains (which are located in [[Uganda]] and the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]). See [http://iahs.info/redbooks/a126/iahs_126_0197.pdf Proceedings of the Riederalp Workshop, September 1978; Actes de l'Atelier de Riederalp, septembre 1978): IAHS-AISH Publ. no. 126, 1980.]</ref>\n* Mountains of Zimbabwe\n** Volcanoes in Zimbabwe: no active volcanoes\n* [[List of rivers of Zimbabwe|Rivers of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[List of World Heritage Sites in Africa#Zimbabwe|World Heritage Sites in Zimbabwe]]\n\n===Regions of Zimbabwe===\n\nRegions of Zimbabwe\n\n====Ecoregions of Zimbabwe====\n\n[[List of ecoregions in Zimbabwe]]\n\n====Administrative divisions of Zimbabwe====\n[[Image:Zimbabwe.geohive.gif|thumb|350px|right|[[Provinces of Zimbabwe|Administrative divisions of Zimbabwe]]]]\n\n[[Administrative divisions of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Provinces of Zimbabwe]]\n** [[Districts of Zimbabwe]]\n*** [[Municipalities of Zimbabwe]]\n\n=====Provinces of Zimbabwe=====\n\n[[Provinces of Zimbabwe]]\n'''[[Zimbabwe]]''' is divided into 8 [[province]]s and 2 cities with provincial status:\n# [[Bulawayo]] (city)\n# [[Harare]] (city)\n# [[Manicaland]]\n# [[Mashonaland Central]]\n# [[Mashonaland East]]\n# [[Mashonaland West]]\n# [[Masvingo Province|Masvingo]]\n# [[Matabeleland North]]\n# [[Matabeleland South]]\n# [[Midlands, Zimbabwe|Midlands]]\n\n=====Districts of Zimbabwe=====\n\n[[Districts of Zimbabwe]]\nThe [[Provinces of Zimbabwe]] are divided into 59 districts and 1,200 municipalities. The districts are listed below, by province:\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-3}}\n; [[Bulawayo|Bulawayo (city)]]\n* [[Bulawayo]]\n\n; [[Harare|Harare (city)]]\n* [[Harare]]\n\n; [[Manicaland|Manicaland Province]]\n* [[Buhera District|Buhera]]\n* [[Chimanimani District|Chimanimani]]\n* [[Chipinge District|Chipinge]]\n* [[Makoni District|Makoni]]\n* [[Mutare District|Mutare]]\n* [[Mutasa District|Mutasa]]\n* [[Nyanga District|Nyanga]]\n\n; [[Mashonaland Central|Mashonaland Central Province]]\n* [[Bindura]]\n* [[Guruve]]\n* [[Mazowe]]\n* [[Mukumbura]]\n* [[Muzarabani]]\n* [[Shamva]]\n\n{{Col-3}}\n; [[Mashonaland East|Mashonaland East Province]]\n* [[Chikomba]]\n* [[Goromonzi]]\n* [[Hwedza]]\n* [[Marondera]]\n* [[Murehwa]]\n* [[Mutoko]]\n* [[Uzumba-Maramba-Pfungwe]]\n\n; [[Mashonaland West|Mashonaland West Province]]\n* [[Chegutu]]\n* [[Kadoma District|Kadoma]]\n* [[Kariba (District)|Kariba]]\n* [[Makonde (District)|Makonde]]\n* [[Zvimba]]\n\n; [[Masvingo Province]]\n* [[Bikita]]\n* [[Chiredzi]]\n* [[Chivi]]\n* [[Gutu]]\n* [[Masvingo]]\n* [[Mwenezi]]\n* [[Zaka District|Zaka]]\n\n{{Col-3}}\n; [[Matabeleland North|Matabeleland North Province]]\n* [[Binga District|Binga]]\n* [[Bubi District|Bubi]]\n* [[Hwange]]\n* [[Lupane District|Lupane]]\n* [[Nkayi District, Zimbabwe|Nkayi]]\n* [[Tsholotsho]]\n* [[Umguza]]\n\n; [[Matabeleland South|Matabeleland South Province]]\n* [[Beitbridge]]\n* [[Bulilimamangwe]]\n* [[Gwanda]]\n* [[Insiza]]\n\n; [[Midlands, Zimbabwe|Midlands Province]]\n* [[Chirumhanzu]]\n* [[Gokwe District|Gokwe North]]\n* [[Gokwe District|Gokwe South]]\n* [[Gweru]]\n* [[Kwekwe]]\n* [[Mberengwa District|Mberengwa]]\n* [[Shurugwi]]\n* [[Zvishavane]]\n{{Col-end}}\n\n=====Municipalities of Zimbabwe=====\n\n[[Municipalities of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Capital (political)|Capital]] of Zimbabwe: [[Capital of Zimbabwe|Harare]]\n* [[List of cities in Zimbabwe|Cities of Zimbabwe]]\n** Largest cities:\n*** [[Harare]]\n*** [[Bulawayo]]\n*** [[Chitungwiza]]\n*** [[Mutare]]\n*** [[Gweru]]\n*** [[Kwekwe]]\n*** [[Kadoma, Zimbabwe|Kadoma]]\n*** [[Masvingo]]\n*** [[Chinhoyi]]\n*** [[Marondera]]\n\n===Demography of Zimbabwe===\n\n[[Demographics of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[HIV/AIDS in Zimbabwe]]\n\n==Government and politics of Zimbabwe==\n[[Image:Harare from the Kopje.jpg|right|thumb|300px|Harare, the capital of Zimbabwe]]\n\n[[Politics of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Form of government]]: [[semi-presidential system|semi-presidential]] [[republic]]\n* [[Capital (political)|Capital]] of Zimbabwe: [[Capital of Zimbabwe|Harare]]\n* [[Politics of Rhodesia]]\n* [[Elections in Zimbabwe]]\n** Zimbabwean presidential elections\n*** {{Hlist| [[Zimbabwean presidential election, 1990|1990]]| [[Zimbabwean presidential election, 1996|1996]]| [[Zimbabwean presidential election, 2002|2002]]| [[Zimbabwean presidential election, 2008|2008]]}}\n** Zimbabwean and Rhodesian parliamentary elections\n*** {{Hlist| [[File:Flag of BSAC edit.svg|22px|border|link=British South Africa Company]] [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1899|1899]]| [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1902|1902]]| [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1905|1905]]| [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1908|1908]]| [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1911|1911]]| [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1914|1914]]| [[Southern Rhodesian Legislative Council election, 1920|1920]]| [[File:Flag of Southern Rhodesia (1924\u20131964).svg|22px|border|link=Southern Rhodesia]] [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1924|1924]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1928|1928]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1933|1933]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1934|1934]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1939|1939]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1946|1946]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1948|1948]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1954|1954]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1958|1958]]| [[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1962|1962]]| [[File:Flag of Rhodesia (1964\u20131968).svg|22px|border|link=Rhodesia]] [[Rhodesian general election, 1965|1965]]| [[File:Flag of Rhodesia (1968\u20131979).svg|22px|border|link=Rhodesia]] [[Rhodesian general election, 1970|1970]]| [[Rhodesian general election, 1974|1974]]| [[Rhodesian general election, 1977|1977]]| [[File:Flag of Zimbabwe Rhodesia.svg|22px|border|link=Zimbabwe Rhodesia]] [[Zimbabwe Rhodesia general election, 1979|1979]]| {{Flagicon|Zimbabwe}}[[Southern Rhodesian general election, 1980|1980]]| [[Zimbabwean parliamentary election, 1985|1985]]| [[Zimbabwean parliamentary election, 1990|1990]]| [[Zimbabwean parliamentary election, 1995|1995]]| [[Zimbabwean parliamentary election, 2000|2000]]| [[Zimbabwean parliamentary election, 2005|2005]]| [[Zimbabwean parliamentary election, 2008|2008]]}}\n* [[Land reform in Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Liberalism in Zimbabwe]]\n* [[List of political parties in Zimbabwe|Political parties in Zimbabwe]]\n** [[Operation Murambatsvina]]\n** [[Zimbabwe Revenue Authority]]\n\n===Branches of the government of Zimbabwe===\n\n[[Government of Zimbabwe]]\n<!-- the following government branches and links do not apply to all countries. Modify as needed, and then remove this line when complete. -->\n\n====Executive branch of the government of Zimbabwe====\n* [[Head of state]]: [[President of Zimbabwe]], [[Robert Mugabe]]\n** [[List of Presidents of Zimbabwe|Previous presidents of Zimbabwe]]\n* [[Head of government]]: [[Prime Minister of Zimbabwe]], [[Morgan Tsvangirai]]\n* [[Cabinet of Zimbabwe]]\n\n====Legislative branch 